# OpenPill General Behaviour

- Keep `SOUL.md` in mind as the high-level product intent and tone.
- Be intellectually honest and constructive:
  - Do not "just agree"; give respectful pushback when trade-offs or risks matter.
  - Prefer truth-seeking over pleasing phrasing.
- Keep a local-first mindset:
  - Prefer local model paths and conservative defaults.
  - Treat external model usage as opt-in and cost-sensitive.
- Preserve backward compatibility unless explicitly changing contracts:
  - Keep legacy env var fallbacks where already supported.
  - If API/MCP payloads change, update docs and tests in the same change.
- Make safe, incremental changes:
  - Avoid destructive operations and avoid reverting unrelated user edits.
  - Prefer small patches over broad refactors unless requested.
- Validate behavior after substantive edits:
  - Run focused tests for touched areas.
  - If OpenAPI shape changes intentionally, update the contract snapshot test.
- Keep docs operationally useful:
  - Reflect new env vars in `README.md` and `docs/OPS.md`.
  - Document rollout defaults and explicit opt-in flags.
- For UI additions in `static/index.html`:
  - Keep controls optional and default-off for experimental features.
  - Ensure new controls degrade gracefully when backend flags are disabled.
- Conversation flow discipline:
  - If the user asks an intermediate question, answer it and then explicitly resume the prior implementation thread when still relevant.
  - Do not drop previously agreed high-value proposals without stating why.
- Suggest next steps only when they add clear value:
  - Avoid always proposing a "next step" by default.
  - Offer one only when timing, risk, or momentum makes it genuinely useful.
- Git commit hygiene:
  - Do not use `git commit --trailer`.
  - Keep commit messages plain unless the user explicitly asks for trailers/footers.
- Prefer project automation commands over ad-hoc command chains:
  - Use `make` targets from `Makefile` first (e.g. `make mongo-up`, `make test-unit`, `make ci-local`).
  - If a requested workflow has no target yet, add one before repeating long manual command sequences.
- For memory retrieval questions in development:
  - Prefer OpenPill tool flow over guessing from stale context.
  - Use `semantic_search` first, then `get_pill` / `get_pill_neighbors` as needed.
  - Use the project shortcuts (`make tool-*` / `scripts/openpill_tools.sh`) to execute these quickly.
- For markdown memory automation:
  - Prefer autonomous changed-file ingestion over manual one-off prompts.
  - Use `scripts/ingest_markdown_memory.py` (or `make md-watch`) to ingest changed `.md` files with idempotency.
